<section id=3D"description">
    <h1>
        Converting Running Speeds and Paces       =20
    </h1>   =20

    <div class=3D"details content">
       =20
        <a target=3D"_blank" href=3D"https://runbundle.com/tools/running-pa=
ce-speed-conversion-calculator" data-google-interstitial=3D"false"></a>
       =20
        <p>Treadmills tend to show speeds in miles per hour or kilometers p=
er hour, whereas running watches (and runners) tend to work in minutes per =
mile or minutes per kilometer. Not many runners consider meters per second,=
 although it's occasionally of interest to sprinters.</p>
      =20
       =20
               =20
                           =20
       =20
        <p>Our pace/speed calculator allows you to quickly between differen=
t running speeds and paces, and also finish times for 5k, 10k, the half mar=
athon and the marathon.</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_1_tablet" class=3D"a=
dthrive-ad adthrive-content adthrive-content-1 adthrive-ad-cls" style=3D"mi=
n-height: 250px;"></div>
       =20
        <p>Fill in any field and all the other fields will update. The conv=
ersion is automatic and instant.</p>
       =20
        <p>You can also generate a summary of speeds/paces/finish times whi=
ch, in addition to summarising the values on the page, also shows finish ti=
mes for a variety of track and road races, and adds some useful (and some n=
ot so useful, but possibly interesting) speed comparisons.</p>
           =20
        <p><a href=3D"https://runbundle.com/tools/running-pace-speed-conver=
sion-calculator#pace-conversion-form" data-google-interstitial=3D"false">=
=E2=86=91 go to calculator</a></p>       =20
               =20
            =20
               =20
    </div>
</section>
       =20
   =20
<section id=3D"how-it-workd">
    <h1>
        How Speeds &amp; Paces are Converted       =20
    </h1>   =20
   =20
   =20

    <div class=3D"details content">
       =20
       =20
        <h2>The difference between pace and speed</h2>
       =20
        <p>The difference between pace and speed is that pace is measured a=
s time per distance, and speed is measured as distance per time.</p>
       =20
            =20
       =20
       =20
        <p>Runners tend to use pace to work how fast they're running. I.e. =
minutes per mile or minutes per kilometer. Although, strangely, many treadm=
ills default to showing speed in miles per hour or kilometers per hour.</p>
       =20
        <h2>Converting between miles per hour and kilometers per hour</h2>
       =20
        <p>One mile is 1609.344 meters, and one kilometer is 1000 meters, s=
o to convert from miles per hour to kilometers per hour we multiply by 1.60=
9344:</p>
       =20
        <blockquote>
            <code>kph =3D mph =C3=97 1.609344 </code>
        </blockquote>

        <p>To convert from kilometers per hour to miles per hour we divide =
by this value:</p>
       =20
        <blockquote>
            <code>mph =3D kph =C3=B7 1.609344</code>
        </blockquote><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_2_tablet" class=3D"adthriv=
e-ad adthrive-content adthrive-content-2 adthrive-ad-cls" style=3D"min-heig=
ht: 250px;"></div>
       =20
                 =20
       =20
       =20
        <h2>Converting between minutes per mile and minutes per kilometer</=
h2>
       =20
        <p>This is very similar to converting between mph and kph as descri=
bed above. However the calculation needs to be carried out with seconds. To=
 convert from mins/mile to mins/km, we first need to convert minutes and se=
conds to seconds. They can then be converted back to minutes and seconds af=
ter the calculation has been carried out.</p>
       =20
        <blockquote>
            <code>seconds per kilometer =3D seconds per mile =C3=B7 1.60934=
4</code>
        </blockquote>         =20
       =20
       =20
        <p>To convert from mins/kilometer to mins/mile:</p>
       =20
        <blockquote>
            <code>seconds per mile =3D seconds per kilometer =C3=97 1.60934=
4</code>
        </blockquote>     =20
               =20
       =20
                   =20
       =20
        <h2>Converting speeds to meters per second</h2>

        <p>This is easily achieved by first converting distance to meters a=
nd converting hours to seconds (by multiplying by 3600, the number of secon=
ds in an hour). Then finally dividing by the number of seconds so that the =
speed is given in number of meters per single second.</p>
       =20
        <p>To convert from miles per hour to meters per second:</p>
       =20
        <blockquote>
            <code>meters per second =3D (miles =C3=97 1609.344) =C3=B7 (hou=
rs =C3=97 3600)</code>
        </blockquote>     =20
       =20
       =20
       =20
       =20
        <p>To convert from kilometers per hour to meters per second:</p>
       =20
        <blockquote>
            <code>meters per second =3D (miles =C3=97 1000) =C3=B7 (hours =
=C3=97 3600)</code>
        </blockquote>             =20
       =20
        <p>Carrying out the calculations in the other direction is simlar, =
but involves dividing the units rather than multiplying them.</p>
       =20
        <p>To convert from meters per second to miles per hour:</p>
       =20
        <blockquote>
            <code>miles per hour =3D (meters =C3=B7 1609.344) =C3=B7 (secon=
ds =C3=B7 3600)</code>
        </blockquote>             =20


        <p>To convert from meters per second to kilometers per hour:</p>
       =20
        <blockquote>
            <code>miles per hour =3D (meters =C3=B7 1000) =C3=B7 (seconds =
=C3=B7 3600)</code>
        </blockquote>             =20
                  =20
       =20
                <p class=3D"section-link">   =20
                    <a class=3D"sec-b" href=3D"https://runbundle.com/tools/=
pace-tables/" data-google-interstitial=3D"false">Pace tables</a>
                </p>            =20
       =20
       =20
               =20
                   =20
                       =20
               =20
    </div>
</section>
